{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487092","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487092"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:57:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:57:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"251"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"251","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/251"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.14,0.08,0.12,0.47]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"251"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112065"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"251","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/251"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"251"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94131"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4626"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5029"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10419"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14665"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16391"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37165"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45916"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112065","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112065"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 74-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-hour history of right-sided weakness affecting his arms and legs. Since this morning, his pronunciation of words has been \u0022a little off\u0022 but he otherwise understands, comprehends, and responds normally. He is not confused or agitated and denies headache, nausea, vomiting, or fever. He has a medical history of hypertension and hyperlipidaemia. He takes amlodipine and atorvastatin. He has a 30 pack-year smoking history and drinks two glasses of wine daily.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with pulse rate 82/min, blood pressure 165/95 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Neurological examination reveals power of 2/5 for all movements on the right side and 5/5 on the left side. There is loss of vibration and proprioception in the right limbs. The tongue deviates to the left on protrusion.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following vessels is most likely occluded?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anterior spinal artery","Posterior inferior cerebellar artery","Posterior spinal artery","Right anterior inferior cerebellar artery","Left anterior inferior cerebellar artery"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic triad of medial medullary syndrome (Dejerine syndrome): contralateral hemiparesis, contralateral loss of proprioception and vibration sense, and ipsilateral hypoglossal nerve palsy. The medial medulla is supplied by the anterior spinal artery and its branches, making occlusion of this vessel the most likely cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnterior spinal artery\u003C/strong\u003E occlusion causes infarction of the medial medulla. The resulting syndrome includes: (1) contralateral hemiparesis from damage to the pyramidal tract before its decussation, (2) contralateral loss of proprioception and vibration from damage to the medial lemniscus after its decussation, and (3) ipsilateral hypoglossal nerve palsy causing tongue deviation towards the affected side. This patient\u0027s right-sided weakness, right-sided proprioceptive loss, and leftward tongue deviation indicate a left medial medullary infarct.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPosterior inferior cerebellar artery\u003C/strong\u003E occlusion causes lateral medullary syndrome (Wallenberg syndrome), characterised by ipsilateral facial sensory loss, contralateral body sensory loss to pain and temperature, dysphagia, hoarseness, vertigo, and ipsilateral ataxia. The preservation of proprioception and vibration sense distinguishes this from medial medullary syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPosterior spinal artery\u003C/strong\u003E occlusion primarily affects the dorsal columns of the spinal cord, causing isolated loss of proprioception and vibration below the lesion level without motor weakness or cranial nerve involvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight anterior inferior cerebellar artery\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003ELeft anterior inferior cerebellar artery\u003C/strong\u003E occlusions both cause lateral pontine syndrome, featuring ipsilateral facial paralysis (CN VII), hearing loss and vertigo (CN VIII), facial sensory loss (CN V), and ipsilateral ataxia. Neither would cause the combination of findings seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe following table summarises the key distinguishing features of these brainstem vascular syndromes:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Ctable border=\u00221\u0022 style=\u0022border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%;\u0022\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Cth style=\u0022padding: 8px; text-align: left;\u0022\u003EArtery\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth style=\u0022padding: 8px; text-align: left;\u0022\u003ESyndrome\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth style=\u0022padding: 8px; text-align: left;\u0022\u003EKey Features\u003C/th\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd style=\u0022padding: 8px;\u0022\u003EAnterior spinal artery\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd style=\u0022padding: 8px;\u0022\u003EMedial medullary\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd style=\u0022padding: 8px;\u0022\u003EContralateral hemiparesis, contralateral proprioceptive loss, ipsilateral CN XII palsy\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd style=\u0022padding: 8px;\u0022\u003EPosterior inferior cerebellar artery\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd style=\u0022padding: 8px;\u0022\u003ELateral medullary\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd style=\u0022padding: 8px;\u0022\u003EIpsilateral facial sensory loss, contralateral body pain/temperature loss, dysphagia, ataxia\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd style=\u0022padding: 8px;\u0022\u003EPosterior spinal artery\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd style=\u0022padding: 8px;\u0022\u003EDorsal column\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd style=\u0022padding: 8px;\u0022\u003EIsolated proprioceptive/vibration loss below lesion\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd style=\u0022padding: 8px;\u0022\u003EAnterior inferior cerebellar artery\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd style=\u0022padding: 8px;\u0022\u003ELateral pontine\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd style=\u0022padding: 8px;\u0022\u003EIpsilateral CN VII palsy, hearing loss, facial sensory loss, ataxia\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003C/table\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Anterior spinal artery occlusion causes medial medullary syndrome with contralateral hemiparesis, contralateral loss of proprioception and vibration, and ipsilateral hypoglossal nerve palsy.","Tongue deviation occurs towards the side of the lesion in hypoglossal nerve palsy, helping localise the brainstem infarct.","Different vascular territories in the brainstem produce distinct clinical syndromes that can be differentiated by careful neurological examination."],"references":["Blumenfeld, H 2010, \u2018Chapter 14 Brainstem III: Internal Structures and Vascular Supply\u2019,\u00a0Neuroanatomy through clinical cases, Second edition. Sunderland, Mass.: Sinauer Associates."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94131"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"251"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94131","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94131"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-24T17:06:49+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-24T17:38:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"251"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112065"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1984","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1984"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddd1\u200d\ud83c\udf3e","name":"Rural \u0026 Remote Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2023-08-28T22